        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "I'm not 100% sure that this is a bug, or whether or not I'm using locales inappropriately, however by relying on the en_GB locale and allowing everything to hook into that, such as Zend_Date, ZendX_JQuery, etc. is yielding unexpected results when converting the date format.\r\n\r\nThe date format for en_GB long and medium is \"d MMM y\", which when converted from the user input to ISO gets you an unexpected result.\r\n\r\nFor example - \r\nUser input is \"1 Jan 10\", which is validated by ZF\r\nWhen converted to ISO format this yields 0010-01-01.. etc.\r\n\r\nWhilst I totally understand why, it would seem more appropriate for the dateformat for long and short to be \"d MMM yyyy\" by default."
        },
